 this book explores how Black, white, and new Latino Mississippians have lived and understood these transformations. Activist anthropologist Angela Stuesse argues that people’s racial identifications and relationships to the poultry industry prove vital to their interpretations of the changes they are experiencing. Illuminating connections between the area’s long history of racial inequality, the industry’s growth and drive to lower labor costs, immigrants’ contested place in contemporary social relations, and workers’ prospects for political mobilization, Scratching Out a Living paints a compelling ethnographic portrait of neoliberal globalization and calls for organizing strategies that bring diverse working communities together in mutual construction of a more just future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAfrican AmericanszMississippixSocial conditions. 0aChicken industryzMississippixSocial conditions. 0aForeign workers, Latin AmericanzMississippixSocial conditions. 0aIndustrial relationszMississippi. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aafrican american workers.  aamerican migrants.  aamerican workforce.  ablack and immigrant labor.  ablack workers.  achicken processing.  aethnic studies.  aexploitative labor practices.  ahispanic american studies.  aindustrial food production.  alatin american immigrants.  alatinx immigration.  alatinx in the us south.  amississippi labor.  aneoliberal globalization.  apoultry industry.  arace and labor.  aracial inequality in the us.  aracial inequality.  aworking class inequality.  aworking class.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831106675470 cprintz978052028720440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096239240uhttps://ww